          "body": "Genesis 24 is the longest chapter in Genesis, and its length is a deliberate narrative choice — the author uses 67 verses where 10 would suffice for the bare facts. The retelling of the well-scene in the servant's report (vv.42-48) alone consumes a third of the chapter. This is not inefficiency; it is theological argument by accumulation. The narrator wants the reader to feel the precision of God's answer: the exact words of the sign were spoken, the exact woman appeared, the exact family connection was confirmed, all before the prayer was finished (v.15). Genesis 24 is a chapter about divine providence — invisible, unannounced, working through ordinary social mechanisms (a servant's journey, a well, a family dinner, a girl's consent) to accomplish a covenantal end that depends on divine faithfulness, not human ingenuity."
