        "title": "The oath under the thigh — a commission grounded in covenant promise",
        "range": "24:1-9",
        "excerpt": "The LORD, the God of heaven, who took me from my father's house and from the land of my birth, and who spoke to me and who swore to me, saying, 'To your descendants I will give this land,' He will send His angel before you.",
        "body": "The chapter opens with a dual statement of status: Abraham is old, and the LORD has blessed him in every way (v.1). These two facts create the chapter's urgency. Advanced age means the patriarch's direct supervision of covenant affairs is nearly over; comprehensive blessing means the promise is already in motion and must not be interrupted by Isaac dying without an heir. The commission that follows is not therefore a private family arrangement but a covenant necessity.\n\nThe oath taken 'under the thigh' (vv.2-3) is the most solemn form of binding oath known in the ancient Near East. The thigh-gesture in patriarchal culture is associated with the procreative capacity — swearing by the life-producing power of the patriarch's body — which makes it peculiarly fitting for an oath about the continuity of the covenant line. The same gesture will appear in Genesis 47:29 when Jacob binds Joseph to bury him in Canaan. John Calvin noted that Abraham 'employs this solemn ceremony to show how earnestly he desires the fulfillment of what he enjoins' (Commentary on Genesis, 24:2).\n\nThe two prohibitions — no Canaanite wife, do not return Isaac to Mesopotamia — are equally weighted and equally theological. A Canaanite wife would threaten covenant purity (cf. Deuteronomy 7:3-4; Genesis 9:25); returning Isaac to Mesopotamia would abandon the promised land and reverse Abraham's own obedience in Genesis 12. Abraham is not merely managing cultural preferences; he is guarding the theological conditions under which the covenant can be transmitted.\n\nAbraham's confidence (vv.7-8) is grounded in prior divine acts: the LORD took him, spoke to him, swore to him. The servant's mission rests not on the servant's competence but on the God who has already demonstrated covenant faithfulness in bringing Abraham this far. 'He will send His angel before you' (v.7) — the angel is not a good-luck charm but the agent of the same God who has been acting since Genesis 12. This confidence produces the one contingency clause (v.8): if the woman will not come, the servant is released from the oath, but Isaac must still not return. The oath is serious; the covenant land is more serious.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yarekh* (thigh, v.2) — also used of the hip-socket in Genesis 32:25 and for the loins in Genesis 46:26. The semantic field involves both physical strength and generative life. *Maleakh* (angel, v.7) — messenger, one sent; the same word for both human and divine messengers. Here it refers to the divine emissary who will superintend the servant's journey, as the angel of the LORD attended Abraham's own journey from Haran."
