        "title": "Prayer at the well — specific asking, immediate answer, instant worship",
        "range": "24:10-27",
        "excerpt": "Before he had finished speaking, behold, Rebekah who was born to Bethuel the son of Milcah, the wife of Abraham's brother Nahor, came out with her jar on her shoulder.",
        "body": "The servant arrives at Nahor's city and positions himself at the well at evening — the daily water-drawing hour. His positioning is practical wisdom, not magic: he goes where women will come, at the time they come. But what follows is not technique; it is prayer. The servant's prayer (vv.12-14) is a model of specific, theologically grounded petition. He addresses God as 'the God of my master Abraham' — identifying the covenant relationship as the ground of his request. He asks for 'success today' — specific, time-anchored, tied to the present mission. And he proposes a sign: if a young woman offers not only to water him but also, unprompted, to water the camels, let her be the one God has appointed for Isaac.\n\nThe proposed sign is not presumptuous; it is discerning. The servant is looking for a quality of character — generous initiative, hospitable self-sacrifice — not a magical coincidence. Ten thirsty camels require roughly 250 gallons of water drawn by hand. A woman who volunteers for that labor, for a stranger she has not met, possesses the kind of servant-hearted character fit to enter the covenant family. The sign is simultaneously a prayer for guidance and a character test embedded in ordinary life. Chuck Swindoll observed that the servant 'doesn't ask for spectacular intervention but for observable confirmation through natural means' (Hand Me Another Brick, adapted).\n\nThe timing of the answer is the chapter's most theologically emphatic moment: 'before he had finished speaking, behold, Rebekah came out' (v.15). The narrator uses 'behold' (*hinneh*) — the Hebrew presentative particle that signals a sudden, surprising appearance — to mark the immediacy. God's answer was already in motion while the prayer was still being spoken. This is not coincidence the narrator is recording; it is divine initiative preceding human petition (cf. Isaiah 65:24: 'Before they call I will answer').\n\nThe servant watches in silence (v.21), gazing at Rebekah while she waters the camels, 'to know whether the LORD had made his journey successful or not.' His silence is pastoral wisdom — he does not interrupt the sign while it is being fulfilled. When the camels finish, he adorns her (v.22), asks her identity (v.23), and the answer confirms genealogical exactness: the daughter of Bethuel, Nahor's son, the son of Abraham's own brother (v.24). The servant's response is immediate prostration and worship (vv.26-27). He does not first check his calendar, or his supply inventory, or his return route. He bows. The doxology of verse 27 — 'the LORD has not forsaken His lovingkindness and His truth toward my master' — is the chapter's theological summit, naming the providential encounter at the well as a direct expression of Yahweh's covenant character.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chesed we-emet* (lovingkindness and truth, v.27) — the standard covenant pair; Exodus 34:6 uses the same two words in the self-declaration of Yahweh. *Hinneh* (behold, v.15) — the presentative particle that signals a sudden scene-change to the narrator's point of view; its use here is emphatically epiphanic. *Tsalach* (made his journey successful, v.21) — to rush upon, to prosper; in theological contexts always implies divine agency moving through events."
